      · Non-standardized split adjustment means that, unlike public exchanges which automatically adjust historical quotes for splits on the effective date, private secondary platforms adjust at different times and using different conventions.
      · Divergent share-count methodologies mean that private platforms often rely on stale or incomplete capitalization data, such as excluding recently issued merger consideration, unconverted preferred, or newly reclassified share classes.
      · Derived vs. matched-trade pricing means that Forge's price is a proprietary derived indicator based on a model incorporating primary funding rounds, bids/asks, and secondary transactions, while NPM's estimate is based on matched-trade data, market activity, and proprietary valuation models.
      · Illiquidity and thin trading means that individual transactions may not be representative of broad market consensus, and quoted prices can reflect stale data or outlier trades.
      · Right of First Refusal (ROFR) and transfer restrictions suppress transaction volume, limit price discovery, and create a wedge between indicative quotes and actual executable prices.
      · Information asymmetry means that prior to the S-1 filing, market participants had limited visibility into SpaceX's consolidated financials, and different platforms may have been working with different information sets.
      · Platform-specific participant pools and fee structures mean that different platforms attract different buyer/seller populations and charge varying fees, typically 2–10%, which can create persistent price dispersion across venues.
